    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Normal spoilage is the expected amount of waste inherent in the production process that cannot be eliminated under efficient operating conditions. It is a product cost included in the cost of good units. In process costing, normal spoilage costs are allocated to good units completed and to ending WIP (if spoilage occurs after the WIP inspection point). Abnormal spoilage, by contrast, exceeds normal expectations and is recognized as a loss (period cost) on the income statement — it is not allocated to inventory. The distinction is important: normal spoilage is inventoriable; abnormal spoilage is expensed immediately.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Normal spoilage is considered an unavoidable cost of production, and therefore is treated as a product cost, not a period expense. Period costs are expensed in the period they are incurred, while product costs are attached to inventory.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - Normal spoilage is an inherent part of the production process under efficient operating conditions. Since it's expected, its cost is absorbed by the good units produced, effectively increasing their cost per unit.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - Spoilage does not directly reduce revenue; it increases the cost of goods sold by increasing the cost of the units that *are* sold. Revenue is based on sales price, not production costs.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - An extraordinary item is unusual and infrequent, whereas normal spoilage is a routine and expected part of the production process. Extraordinary items are also reported separately on the income statement, which is not the case for normal spoilage.",
    },
    educational: "In process costing, costs are tracked through various production departments. Normal spoilage is an unavoidable part of this process, and its cost is ultimately borne by the good units that are successfully completed. This ensures that the cost of production accurately reflects the realities of the manufacturing environment.",
    examTip: "Remember the distinction: 'Normal' is inventoriable (product cost), 'Abnormal' is an expense (period cost).",
    memoryAid: "NA",
    reference: "Managerial Accounting — Spoilage Accounting",
