    question: "The step-down (sequential) method of service department cost allocation:",
    options: ["Ignores all service department interactions","Allocates service department costs sequentially, recognizing some inter-service department relationships, but once a department's costs are allocated, it receives no further allocations","Simultaneously allocates costs among all service departments","Allocates costs only to production departments using direct labor hours"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "The step-down method allocates service department costs one at a time in a specified order (typically starting with the department that provides the most service to other service departments). Once a department's costs are fully allocated, it receives no cost back from subsequent allocations. This partially recognizes interdepartmental services (unlike the direct method, which ignores all inter-service relationships). The reciprocal (algebraic/simultaneous equations) method fully accounts for mutual services between all service departments and is the most theoretically accurate but most complex. The direct method is simplest but ignores inter-service relationships entirely.",
