    explanation: "FCF = Cash flow from operations (CFO) − Capital expenditures (CapEx). FCF represents the cash available to the firm after maintaining and investing in its asset base. Uses of FCF include: paying dividends, repurchasing shares, paying down debt, or making acquisitions. Positive FCF indicates the company generates sufficient cash from its operations to fund its capital investments and have cash remaining. Negative FCF may indicate heavy investment for future growth (not necessarily bad). Free cash flow to equity (FCFE) further subtracts net debt payments. FCF yield = FCF ÷ Market capitalization.",
