    explanation: "Divisional ROI = Operating income ÷ Invested capital = (Operating income ÷ Sales) × (Sales ÷ Invested capital) = Margin × Turnover. Margin measures profit efficiency (how much profit per dollar of sales). Turnover measures asset efficiency (how much revenue per dollar of invested capital). A division can improve ROI by: (1) increasing margin (reducing costs or raising prices), (2) increasing turnover (generating more revenue from the same asset base), or (3) both. ROI is widely used but has limitations: it can discourage managers from investing in projects that earn above the cost of capital but below the current ROI.",
