    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Target costing is a market-driven approach: Target cost = Market price − Desired profit margin. Rather than setting the price based on cost (cost-plus pricing), target costing sets the cost based on the price the market will bear. If the current expected cost exceeds the target, the company must find ways to reduce costs through value engineering, design changes, process improvements, or supplier negotiations. Target costing is widely used in Japanese manufacturing (Toyota pioneered it) and is applied during the product design stage when ~80% of costs are committed. It encourages cross-functional collaboration (design, engineering, marketing, accounting).",
