    courseId: "cpa",
    section: "BAR",
    blueprintArea: "BAR-III",
    topic: "Performance Measurement",
    subtopic: "EVA",
    difficulty: "hard",
    skillLevel: "Analysis",
    question: "A business unit has NOPAT of $800,000 and invested capital of $5 million. If the company's WACC is 12%, what is the unit's Economic Value Added (EVA) and what does it indicate?",
    options: ["EVA = $400,000 — the unit earns double its capital charge","EVA = $200,000 — the unit creates value above its capital cost","EVA = ($200,000) — the unit destroys shareholder value","EVA = $800,000 — NOPAT equals value created"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "EVA = NOPAT − (Invested Capital × WACC) = $800,000 − ($5,000,000 × 12%) = $800,000 − $600,000 = $200,000. A positive EVA means the unit earns more than its cost of capital, creating economic value for shareholders beyond what they require as compensation for risk.",
