      0: "Why option A is WRONG - The materials quantity variance can always be determined if you know the standard quantity, actual quantity, and standard price.",
      1: "Why option B is WRONG - An unfavorable variance occurs when actual costs are higher than standard costs. Using less material than expected results in a cost savings, not an overspending.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - A zero variance means actual quantity equals standard quantity. Since the actual quantity used is *less* than the standard quantity, the variance is not zero.",
