    correctAnswer: 3,
    explanation: "Sunk costs are past costs that cannot be recovered regardless of the decision made. Only future costs that differ between alternatives (differential costs) are relevant. Examples: past R&D costs, previous investments.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Sunk costs may be recorded in the accounting system; the fact that they are or are not recorded is irrelevant to their decision-making relevance.",
      1: "Why option B is WRONG - Sunk costs can affect both the balance sheet and the income statement, but their impact on financial statements doesn't determine their relevance to future decisions.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - The size of a cost doesn't determine whether it's relevant; even large sunk costs are irrelevant because they cannot be recovered.",
      3: "Why option D is CORRECT - Sunk costs, by definition, are costs that have already been incurred and cannot be recovered or changed by any future decision; therefore, they should be ignored when making future choices.",
    },
    educational: "Relevant costs are future costs that differ between alternatives. Sunk costs are historical costs that are unavoidable regardless of the decision made. Therefore, only incremental or differential costs and revenues should be considered when making business decisions.",
