      1: "Why option B is WRONG - The actual wage rate exceeding the standard wage rate relates to the labor rate variance, not the labor efficiency variance, which focuses solely on hours.",
      2: "Why option C is CORRECT - A favorable labor efficiency variance arises when the actual hours worked are less than the standard hours that should have been worked for the actual level of production, indicating efficient use of labor.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - Production volume being lower than expected might impact overall profitability, but it doesn't directly explain a favorable labor efficiency variance, which is about the efficiency of labor usage relative to output.",
