    difficulty: "easy",
    skillLevel: "Application",
    question: "Gamma Corp., a U.S.-based company, expects to receive €1,000,000 in 90 days from a sale to a European customer. To hedge the foreign currency risk, Gamma entered into a forward contract to sell €1,000,000 in 90 days at a rate of $1.10/€. This forward contract qualifies and is designated as a cash flow hedge. At the end of the first month (30 days), the forward rate for selling €1,000,000 in 60 days is $1.12/€. Assuming no transaction costs, what is the gain or loss recognized in other comprehensive income (OCI) related to the derivative at the end of the first month?",
    options: ["Gain of $20,000","Loss of $20,000","Gain of $10,000","Loss of $10,000"],
    correctAnswer: 0,
    explanation: "The gain or loss on the derivative is calculated as the difference between the original forward rate and the forward rate at the end of the month, multiplied by the amount of the foreign currency. In this case, the gain is (€1,000,000 * ($1.12/$ - $1.10/$)) = $20,000. Since the contract is designated as a cash flow hedge, the gain is reported in OCI (ASC 815).",
